              <p>
                <span>1. Install and Maintain Smoke Alarms: </span>Smoke alarms
                are your first line of defense against fires. Install them on
                every level of your home, including inside bedrooms and outside
                sleeping areas. Test them monthly and replace batteries
                annually.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-section">
              <img
                src="./Images/fire/escape.png"
                width="250px"
                alt=""
                srcset=""
              />
              <p>
                <span>2. Develop and Practice Escape Plan:</span> Create a fire
                escape plan with your family or household members. Practice it
                regularly, ensuring everyone knows the fastest way out of the
                house in case of a fire. Designate a meeting point outside and
                emphasize the importance of staying low and crawling under
                smoke.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-section">
              <img
                src="./Images/fire/fireexting.png"
                width="250px"
                alt=""
                srcset=""
              />
              <p>
                <span>3. Proper Use of Fire Extinguishers: </span>Keep fire
                extinguishers in key locations throughout your home, such as the
                kitchen, garage, and near fireplaces. Learn how to use them
                properly and ensure they are regularly inspected and maintained.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-section">
              <img
                src="./Images/fire/kitchen.png"
                width="250px"
                alt=""
                srcset=""
              />
              <p>
                <span>4. Kitchen Safety:</span> The kitchen is a common area for
                fires to start. Never leave cooking food unattended, keep
                flammable items away from stovetops, and be prepared to smother
                grease fires with a lid and turn off the heat. Ensure all
                appliances are turned off when not in use.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-section">
              <img
                src="./Images/fire/heating.png"
                width="250px  "
                alt=""
                srcset=""
              />
              <p>
                <span>5. Heating Safety:</span> Exercise caution when using
                heating equipment, such as space heaters and fireplaces. Keep
                flammable materials at least three feet away from heat sources,
                and never leave them unattended. Ensure chimneys and vents are
                cleaned and inspected annually.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
